cs.DS, cs.CG, cs.DM, cs.IT, cs.NA. 

The paper deals with a graph problem involving distances and terminals, which suggests that it belongs to the categories of cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) and cs.CG (Computational Geometry). The use of tail bounds on the sum of independent exponential random variables suggests that it may also belong to the category of cs.DM (Discrete Mathematics). The improvement of the distortion bound suggests that it may belong to the category of cs.IT (Information Theory). Finally, the use of a ball-growing algorithm suggests that it may also belong to the category of cs.NA (Numerical Analysis).
